Improve error reporting in _get_my_ipv4_address()

commit_message:
Web UI for freezer

This changes are the first implementation of
the freezer web ui.
It's a read only version that permit to view the backups
in swift made by the user.

Change-Id: I79fd98ce3fc364c7a82a8b764e1733febb16b647

commit_message:
Remove remaining deprecated oslo-incubator modules

Remove remaining reference to gettextutils and remove the module,
as it no longer exists in oslo-incubator.  Also remove timeutils
for the same reason, it's not referenced by any remaining code.

Closes-Bug: #1380629
Change-Id: Ie3ad3fe73fd5e73dd6ede0c375eb2077d95bda3f

commit_message:
Utility function for robust schema drop

Provided utility function which drops schema with all relations. It
doesn't spend time reflecting all the columns and data-types and also can
handle the case where foreign key dependencies are in a cycle between
tables. Postgresql ENUM type deletes.

The function originally authored by Michael Bayer (zzzeek)
https://bitbucket.org/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/wiki/UsageRecipes/DropEverything
The function used at `ModelsMigrationsSync` as an instance method, so it
have been moved out from the class.

Change-Id: Ib884e93ed9d4fe367c55e63a7ead52dc1f720c39

commit_message:
Fix MANIFEST.in to install all py files

I'm currently embedding this patch in my Debian package, as otherwise,
the git-based "python setup.py install" fails to install files within
the oslo/db/openstack folder. This patch fixes it. Please allow this
as I do not want to carry such patch forever in Debian.

Change-Id: Ib708a66313ba3a7ff0e73f9ea72de60bf1cbbb8b

Since action handlers are atom specific it seems appropriate
to place the handlers under a specific submodule so that the
action engine module/folder layout is more obvious and makes

commit_message:
Move atom action handlers to there own subfolder/submodule

Since action handlers are atom specific it seems appropriate
to place the handlers under a specific submodule so that the
action engine module/folder layout is more obvious and makes
more sense.

This also adds on a handles(atom) method to those handlers
so that the runtime module/class can use those methods to
determine which handler should handle resetting an atom to
its initial state.

Change-Id: I7067d91347b41613fba1492d81d68a590f22c467

commit_message:
Remove useless sslutils

This module has been imported but has actually never been used to its
real purpose directly, which was controlling WSGI and RPC server
parameters.

Let's remove it and replace it by the standard and documented SSL
information we have from the currently used WSGI server.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4ddfaffd35bcda29ae743d5f6e699b6daabcaa49

commit_message:
Remove sslutils

It turns out that some projects copy this module over but it's not
actually used by any of these. Patches have been sent to remove it from
these projects:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/126503/
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/126501/
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/126502/

Now let's remove it from the incubator.

Change-Id: Ieecd843b6c41e5ffc72364bdbe2fef039d3039f6

commit_message:
Don't register pool endpoints when pooling=False

We recently enabled admin_mode=True in devstack. This raised an issue
with the way we register endpoints. The redis driver has no support for
pooling yet and this made Zaqar fail when running in admin mode because
it tried to register pool endpoints as well.

Although this issue is a side-effect caused by the missing feature, it
does represent an error and a need to improve the way endpoints are
registered.

Change-Id: I0f65bb25383b889048c900daa657121f64234663
Closes-bug: #1399554

commit_message:
return the dict of port when no sec-group involved

Commit abc16ebf made the get_sg_ids_grouped_by_port function not return
entries for ports without security groups. This causes the agent to not remove
previously created security groups for that port since the port is not
returned in the security_group_info_for_devices data.

This change fixes that by always including a list of security groups for each
port, even if that list is empty.

Change-Id: I9616708462a8b6f3d46ebd76db5cf8cb2826f4ad
Closes-Bug: #1398312

commit_message:
etc: replace NullHandler by Python one

We don't need to specify the NullHandler that was provided by Oslo
anymore, as Python 2.7 has this one. Let's use it directly.

Change-Id: I6948d1cd5a556779c1b1fd0a4161689e3a944b45

commit_message:
Be explicit about publish keyword arguments

Instead of allowing for arbitrary keyword arguments which
makes the API hard to change in the future prefer to have
explicit arguments (and keyword arguments) instead of allowing
**kwargs to be passed.

Change-Id: I374db6b19ef76c2f9ee04771f5d928c79b7cf049

commit_message:
Add a few useful assert methods to the base class

This commit adds a few useful assert functions that
make it easier to have tests check if an item is greater
than another item, an item is greater than or equal to another
item or that a regular expression matches a given piece of
text, or that a callable raises an exception that matches a
given regular expression message.

These currently came from taskflow and would seem to be useful
elsewhere as test functionality that can be leveraged by
other oslotest users.

Change-Id: I95ae1b3edc9319061827d3406146044d92d28cf4

commit_message:
Fix NOVA_API_VERSION option

This patch fixes it.

commit_message:
Implement microversion support on api methods

Adds support for specifying api versioning information
on api methods and the infrastructure to route requests
to the correct method based on the request information.
The api_version decorator allows us to retain the same
method name for different implementations (versions) of
the API method (GET/PUT/POST, etc).

Note that currently the @api_version decorator must
be the first (outermost) decorator on an API method.
We should in future have at least a hacking rule to enforce
this but better would be to remove this restriction.

Partially Implements Blueprint api-microversions

Change-Id: Ifb6698c582d37284c42b9b81100a651fd8d1dd1a

commit_message:
Some package additions and adjustments to the env_builder.sh

This just adjusts to install wget and certain other packages
before further work commences to ensure they are ready and
avaiable for further use.

Tested on rhel6.x as a cloud-init userdata script and it appears
to continue to work as expected.

Change-Id: Ia85715e27bc8342fd61d23e2c8a659dbce20aea9

commit_message:
Split large methods into submethods to reduce max-complexity

By this refactoring max-complexity of PEP8 is reduced from 33 to 19.

Closes-Bug: #1399523
Change-Id: I7e9e5cefd3e72e322d8b327f495ce7fc863c3678

commit_message:
Remove references to defunct swift content

After moving the swift system requirements and example
architecture to the overview chapter, I think we can
safely remove references to the defunct sections in the
swift chapter. A future patch will remove the defunct
files. Also improved some phrasing/wording.

Change-Id: I364f6d21dafbed22990bafb53c828b8e54775f85
Partial-Bug: #1389382
backport: juno
(cherry picked from commit dcfb255c55edbd9c43eb5b7db7a4eea4fc980c96)

commit_message:
Import _LC into auth_token middleware.

_LC wasn't imported with the other log translation methods. It's only
used in one place in auth_token and I can't figure out a way to trigger
it via a test case. I think the whole exception block is now redundant.

Import _LC anyway just in case someone is hitting it.

Change-Id: Ic21d47006d4823a03e0ffc9366256b3f3a0e6531

commit_message:
Delete resource_data after resource deleted

This patch deletes resource_data when the corresponding 
resource is deleted (e.g. in resource.destroy()). 
With this patch, there will be no need to delete 
resource_data deliberately.

Change-Id: I556c757455f1c66b386eda2727a9df34a94fe280

[{'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-10-17 17:51:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-10-17 17:55:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-17 17:58:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm confused about the details of how this works within the driver vs. the capacity filter in the scheduler.

I was assuming that the LVM driver would base free space calculations on this ratio which ensures that it won't over-provision even if there is no capacity filter. (This seems to be the only safe way to do this IMO -- we don't want users to over-provision to infinity even if they aren't using the filter.)

Can you explain then, when the capacity filter is useful vs. not strictly required for this?

Also, does this mean that oversubscription_ratio can be set differently for the scheduler/capacityFilter and each driver backend as well?"}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-17 18:02:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Also, this capability exists already in the NFS driver as nfs_oversub_ratio.  How does this work interact with that existing code?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-17 18:07:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- gate-cinder-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/42/129342/2/check/gate-cinder-specs-python27/00c41fc : FAILURE in 5m 35s'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2014-10-17 18:23:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Would it be possible for the driver to update the "over_subscription_ratio" dynamically for its backend?

I'm thinking more specifically to backends that offer compression/de-dup that they might be able to detect if the ratio is still "optimal" or not and could automatically adjust.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:04:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the feedback!

Eric,
I’m aware that the NFS driver already uses over subscription ratio and used ratio.  I was actually wondering why it was not in the scheduler so that everyone can take advantage of.  You brought up a good point that this proposal will not work if the filter is not used.  If the filter is not used, then the driver is the only place where the check for over subscription and used ratio can happen.  So now it seems to me this mechanism is needed in both the scheduler and the driver.

It is needed in the scheduler so that the scheduler won’t send volume provisioning request to a backend that has exceeded the over subscription ratio or the used ratio, and instead it will send to a valid backend that can fulfill the request.  It is needed in the driver so that this control mechanism will still take effect even if the filter is not used to guarantee that over provisioning won’t happen.  I’ll take a look and see how this can co-exist in both filter and driver.

Currently in my POC, I didn’t set this for each driver backend.  I think it makes sense to let each backend set a different ratio.

Patrick,
Interesting idea on making over-subscription ratio dynamic.  I’m not sure if this ratio will change all the time.  It is an upper limit.  I’m open to suggestions though.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:13:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sounds great, if this can be used in the scheduler and in drivers (and set independently) then I think this is pretty on-target with the requirements from my POV.'}, {'account_id': 10677, 'date': '2014-10-22 16:28:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I support the idea of adding explicit support for over subscription to cinder, but I don't believe that doing it at the backend level will match how users (administrators) will actually want to consume this feature.

I believe administrators would like to link oversubscription (or lack thereof) to volume_types, such that you could have a scheme with:
* Gold (no overscription, ratio=1.0)
* Silver (minor oversubscription, ratio=1.5)
* Bronze (heavy oversubscroption, ratio=3.0)

Setting the oversubscribe amount as an extra spec on the volume_type makes more sense to me than setting it as an attribute of a backend, especially if we're going to allow a specific value rather than an on/off setting. Why would one backend have 200% virtual space while another backend has 300% virtual space?

In order to support oversubscription as an extra_spec, backends only need to report 2 extra capabilities:
* thin_provision (the ability to "create" volumes without consuming space until the space is actually needed -- affects whole backend/pool)
* space_reservation (the ability to "thick provision" individual volumes by within a given backend/pool that supports thin privisioning)

The scheduler can be changed to support oversubscription on a request by request basis by interpretting the oversubscription ratio for each volume as a fractional commit of space. For example, a 3GB volume of type "bronze" (above) would only reduce the comitted free space on a backend by 1GB.

I can provide more details at the weekly meeting if people are interested in this approach.'}, {'account_id': 7546, 'date': '2014-11-24 22:19:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: -Code-Review

@Ben,

I'm coming from the perspective of a Ceph backend (which is already implicitly oversubscribed) operator.

I'm not sure how your alternative would work. To me the value of this spec is that it aims to make oversubscription explicit and allow the operator a measure of control about how aggressive they want to be with it.

I don't see how oversubscription ratio would be practical as a volume_type property (at least for all drivers), because:
* it's not like we have any control over the nature of the data that the user puts into the volume (so we have no idea how effective thin-provisioning will be);
* having it as a volume property would make it useless as an operational/administrative limit on oversubscription (because users are creating and deleting volumes on-demand all the time, we have no control over the relative amount of any specific volume_type that is in use and thus no control on the amount of oversubscription), so that would forgo one of the specs key features;
* what's more, I think with your example gold,silver,bronze types, if such volumes shared the same backend then a bronze volume user could break the backend (by filling it) for gold and silver users.

Presumably the reason one backend may have more virtual space than another would be by virtue of the backend technology. I have limited experience with this, but I assume e.g. Ceph, Netapp, EMC, backends would all achieve different thin-provisioning ratios with the same input volumes based on their inherent implementations and other knobs tweaked independently of the Cinder config. It would only make sense to me to have different ratios per volume_type if the types were tied to different backends (which might be different pools in Ceph).

So I think maybe you are talking about a different, complementary feature? Hope some of that makes sense."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-11-25 05:58:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Thanks everyone for your review!

Hi Ben, 

Using per volume type over subscription ratio is an interesting idea, but I don't think it will work.

The scheduler looks at capacities reported by each backend (or pool) and evaluates whether each backend (or pool) can serve the create volume request.

If over subscription ratio is on per volume type basis, the over subscription ratio will be an extra spec in each volume type.

Let's look at how to use a formula to determine whether the over_subscription_ratio will be exceeded or not.

If virtual_capacity/total_capacity >= over_subscription_ratio, the backend will not be chosen for volume provisioning.

The capacities are reported by a backend or pool (not per volume type).  We can't compare the per backend (or pool) capacities against a per volume type over_subscription_ratio because one volume type can be associated with multiple backends (pools), or a single backend (pool), or one backend (pool) can be used for multiple volume types. 

Unless if Cinder volume driver is reporting capacities per volume type, I don't see how this can work.

I agree with Blair's comments too."}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2014-11-26 15:27:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I left the proposed implementation out of my original comment for brevity sake, but here is what i was thinking:

The scheduler already maintains a list (in memory) of how much available space exists on each backend. Rather than having the backends lie to the scheduler about how much space they have, we would have them continue to tell the truth about space, but the scheduler would decrement the free space by a fractional amount for each new volume it creates, rather than the full amount, which it does today. The scheduler knows the volume type of every volume, and thus it could know the oversubscribe_ratio for each volume, if we chose to make oversubscription an attribute of the volume type rather than the backend.

Thus if you use my numbers above, suppose you have a 100 GB backend, with 20 GB of "gold" volumes, and 30 GB of "silver" volumes and 60 GB of "bronze" volumes, we would compute the free space as:

100 - 20 / 1 - 30 / 1.5 - 60 / 3 = 40 GB

Regarding Blair's comment:

Without space reservation (the second part of my proposal) it's true that bronze users could ruin it for gold users, but many controllers do support a combination of space reserved and non-space reserved volumes such that you can make good on your guarantees to the gold users while still allowing oversubscription of the remaining space.

It's true that there's not a lot of practical difference between a small oversubscription ratio and a large oversubscription ratio when you mix them, but administrators can easily avoid that case by arranging for silver and bronze volumes to land a non-overlapping sets of backends.

The root of my concern here is that implementing oversubscription by making the backends lie to the scheduler removes the possibility for the scheduler to do smart things. Oversubscription always involves telling a lie somewhere, but it's better for that to be done at the highest abstraction layer possible, when the most information is available.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-11-26 15:58:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi Ben,

Regarding your following comment that the scheduler should calculate the "free space" based on its knowledge on all volume types that are supported by a backend, that seems to be very different from the current architecture of how the scheduler and the driver interact with each other.

"we would compute the free space as:
100 - 20 / 1 - 30 / 1.5 - 60 / 3 = 40 GB
"

Currently the scheduler retrieves "free space" (available_capacity) reported by a backend.  The scheduler doesn't calculate the "free space" for a backend. 

So the formula you provided above for calculating the "free space" can be executed by the driver and reported back as available_capacity to the scheduler.  The currently proposal doesn't prevent the driver from doing this, though I still think over subscription ratio should be calculated per backend rather than per volume type (as explained in my previous comments).'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2014-11-27 12:44:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Ah, I finally understand what Ben is getting at!

I'm not sure if it would work well with several thousands of volumes in the db, though you could cache some results for a while.

It would be interesting to see an implementation of that approach, but I think it would be sufficiently different from what we have that it should be done in parallel and tested slowly - there's no significant harm to having two similar filters for a few months while we compare them"}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2014-11-27 14:32:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(2 comments)

A couple of questions inline. I'm not well-versed with the scheduler details, so the questions might be senseless"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-11-27 18:09:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

By examining Ben's formula further, I believe that Ben and I have different interpretation of the term over subscription ratio. What we want to achieve in the end is not that different.  So we should have a discussion first without using the term over subscription ratio. 

Another term used by Ben is "space_reservation". I have verified with him that means thick lun provisioning. 

Use case 1: Each volume type has a separate backend or pool. 
Gold volume type uses "gold" pool, Silver volume type uses "silver" pool, and Bronze volume type uses "bronze" pool. 
The current spec will satisfy what Ben wants to achieve.

Use case 2: One volume type is associated with multiple backends or pools. 
Silver volume type uses pool 1 and pool 2. 
The current spec will satisfy what Ben wants to achieve.

Use case 3: One backend or pool is used by multiple volume types. 
Pool X is used by volume types Gold, Silver, and Bronze.
This is the one that gets a little trickier. 

Using Ben's example, Gold volume type only creates thick luns, Silver volume type creates thick or thin luns, and Bronze volume type creates only thin luns. Since they are sharing the same pool, the calculation can be a little trickier.  

This 3rd use case is supported by the current spec as well, but some details are a little different from Ben's proposal. 

Based on discussions happened at the IRC meeting and after the meeting, I'll be adding a thin/thick extra spec in the volume type. This will address some of Ben's concerns regarding use case #3. We'll discuss more to sort out the remaining differences.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-11-27 18:25:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(2 comments)

Answered Rushi's questions. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-11-28 04:59:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-28 05:00:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

The best I could find in a short amount of time is this etherpad [1] "Shoot for dropping 2.6 support in clients/libraries coincident with ceasing to support 2.6 on stable branches of servers".

That could be old though. If you know otherwise, please provide verification from somewhere that it is ok to remove this now.

[1] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/juno-cross-project-future-of-python'}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2014-12-04 09:14:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ruby,

Thank you for pointing out the important point.
I learned that "py26" issue is not simple, and the situation is different between client and server.

It seems that Infra team made the decision as follows [2]:

> This essentially boils down to: no python26 jobs against server project
> master branches, but python26 jobs continue to run against stable
> branches. Python-*client and oslo projects[1] will continue to have
> python26 jobs run against their master branches. All other projects will
> have python26 jobs completely removed (including stackforge).

So it seems we have to keep "py26" as far as Juno is supported.

[2] https://www.mail-archive.com/openstack-dev@lists.openstack.org/msg40684.html

--
Naohiro'}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2014-12-04 09:29:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Michael, David,

Thank you for reviewing the patch.

I'd like to hear your opinions too.

Enable: H301 one import per line

so we temporarily disable it. Workaround on H302 will
be provided with next bug-fix patch.

Modify glance's sync strategy option

Add a 'nova' option of sync_strategy in glance-sync.conf, which means
sync the image when firsh time the instance is lanuched.

commit_message:
Complete mocking for test_extensions

The current implementation of trove.tests.unittests.api.
common.test_extensions does not fully mock the
test_default_extensions method. As a result trove UTs run without
trove being installed fail in this method as it assumes the
entry points have been installed into the egg for trove.

This patch completes mocking of that method so that the
test_extensions class can be run in a UT environment in
which trove is not installed and thus may not have the entry
points installed to the egg.

Change-Id: I2543f17fe087cf98d1a11ef47a07b4addfd32cd4
Closes-Bug: 1372950

commit_message:
Use real discovery object in auth_token middleware.

Auth token middleware has always done its own version of discovery. It
is slightly more lenient than the one in keystoneclient however we
should use the standard tools for these jobs.

Move the handling of this discovery into the plugin. This is inline with
how auth plugins work and will make it easy to replace with other
plugins.

Change-Id: I3c4ff5bed1aa76dfff8e445de5a384c3f7992bbe

Improve tox.ini

Currently, the tox will run some tests we don't need in this repository,
this patch copies the tox.ini from nova-specs to improve it.

commit_message:
Correct documenting constructor parameters

When the docs are rendered to HTML, any docs on __init__ are not
displayed. The parameters to the constructor have to be documented on
the class rather than on the __init__ method.

Also, corrected other minor issues in the same areas.

Change-Id: Ic56da33f6b99fe5efb636c289e3c4e1569f0c84c

commit_message:
Correct Session docstring

The online docs for the Session class are unusable because the
arguments to __init__ were not displayed.

This and other issues in the docstrings for the class are corrected.

Change-Id: Ia03b785f132f7d21ba576c0c8d634051d7127319

commit_message:
pretty_tox.sh: Portablity improvement

A recent change (commit 0d5a11d9c722870f9c5e31a993219c7e240b4e19)
introduced bash dependency.  It broke my environment, where bash
is not available.  This change aims to restore it.

As far as I undestand, the change in question requires bash for
the "pipefail" feature.  Fortunately there's a more portable
well-known trick for the purpose.

Closes-Bug: #1398266
Change-Id: Id3561d81462923d20ad39584ba4cf8e1a294a8a8

commit_message:
Fix the expression to be python3 compatible.

the oct function in python2 and python3 return different results.
Instead of comparing strings, compare the integer results directly.

Change-Id: Ic802d8dcb27067fa4b1e57eb549565516715c94e

commit_message:
check_params does not need to call sort

This patch removes the unneeded call to sort in check_params and
adds a docstring to what this method does. In addition it adds a note
about us not needing to call this method each a datasource driver calls
update_from_datasource.

Related-bug: 1387185
Change-Id: Ida146aaadc8b6e9b7676c2cc72c479f4e8edf263

commit_message:
Move inline function _get_schema outside of get_schema

This patch pulls the inline method _get_schema outside of the method
get_schema in an attempt to improved readability. Inline functions are
generally dangerous to use if they are long, in addition one needs to
gernally take special care in variable scoping from the outter function which
can be error prone. This similar clean up should also be done in other places
but this patch just handles get_schema for now.

Change-Id: I4cb77eaa82d76434f172dc0f644007d047b817b2

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow

commit_message:
Connecting REST API to DB, part II

In models.py (DB models)
* updated CLUSTER_STATUSES data structure to class for easier
  indexing and ability to add more extensions to statuses
* updated DB schema to make status a mandatory column

In api.py (DB api)
* added delete_cluster support
* added get_cluster support
* added get_clusters support

In v1.api (cue/api)
* completed support for get/list all clusters
* completed support for delete a cluster
* completed support for get a cluster

In test_models.py (DB models)
* Updated deleting tests to conform with new api

Change-Id: I3328556f482619dea9957827bfc44cac2b2373aa

commit_message:
Fix badly named function _get_kernel_params()

Renamed _get_kernel_params() to _get_agent_params() and
appropriate module-level attribute KPARAMS to APARAMS.

Updated agent tests to match new function name.

Change-Id: I4cdf1defee7487785967a092c81c906d40bf3214
Closes-Bug: #1367917

commit_message:
Rework the old logo

* Re-work the old banner logo for the Sphinx docs
* Remove the remaining leftover assets from the old web site

So this is one possibility, I retained the other logo files so we have
options to play with.

commit_message:
Enforce log hints in neutron.plugins.plumgrid

This change enforces log hints use and removes debug level log
translation, modifications are validated through a hacking rule and
the change respects loggging guidelines.

Validate that hacking rules apply to directories:
    - neutron/plugins/plumgrid

Change-Id: Ie85abb93cdbe50bdd56c9f987784baf4c4dd631d
Partial-bug: #1320867

commit_message:
Remove check_uptodate.sh check from tox.ini

This removes the check_uptodate.sh test from the py2* tox envs and
run_tests.sh. It also syncs the sample config one last time to document
some new options available to users running with the newer
oslo.messaging versions.

Change-Id: I6107b996d5da808c3222696a9549ee06c22f80b9
Closes-bug: #1399085

commit_message:
Remove check_uptodate.sh check from tox.ini

This removes the check_uptodate.sh test from the pep8 tox env. It
also syncs the sample config one last time to document some new
options available to users running with the newer oslo.messaging
versions.

Change-Id: I6107b996d5da808c3222696a9549ee06c22f80b9
Closes-bug: #1399085

commit_message:
Update metering unit selection to use smaller units for time

Update the unit selection to not convert to a higher unit until
the max value is at least 2 units.

Change-Id: I349b328b553ed634a70b70b695d4db92295c9b67
Closes-bug: #1384248

[{'created': '2014-12-04 20:58:29.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Fix Brocade FC SAN lookup MITM vulnerability"

This reverts commit ab4f57212683baec45d5b682bdd3952ff58249ed.

The change is being reverted as it broke the Brocade FC SAN lookup
functionality.  The change uses configuration options from
ssh_utils that are not initialized when the Brocade driver is
run causing an exception to be thrown complaining that
CONF.ssh_hosts_key_file is used before it is initialized.

The right solution is to change the Brocade driver to use ssh_utils to
make SSH connections.

Conflicts:

	cinder/zonemanager/drivers/brocade/brcd_fc_san_lookup_service.py

Change-Id: I7814c3da9c0e6fcf3143969e74304a48cafcb3d1
Closes-bug: 1398488
(cherry-picked from commit 57103807c5e7fad7276f97ac82f8704f17f4b846)
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Fix Brocade FC SAN lookup MITM vulnerability"

This reverts commit ab4f57212683baec45d5b682bdd3952ff58249ed.

The change is being reverted as it broke the Brocade FC SAN lookup
functionality.  The change uses configuration options from
ssh_utils that are not initialized when the Brocade driver is
run causing an exception to be thrown complaining that
CONF.ssh_hosts_key_file is used before it is initialized.

The right solution is to change the Brocade driver to use ssh_utils to
make SSH connections.

Conflicts:

	cinder/zonemanager/drivers/brocade/brcd_fc_san_lookup_service.py

Change-Id: I7814c3da9c0e6fcf3143969e74304a48cafcb3d1
Closes-bug: 1398488
(cherry-picked from commit 57103807c5e7fad7276f97ac82f8704f17f4b846)

commit_message:
Log early boot of Ironic VMs to serial with sgabios

This adds sgabios to the list of packages for Ironic and configures
the libvirt domain to redirect BIOS messages to serial via sgabios,
when console logging is enabled.  The sgabios package in Ubuntu
currently has an apparmor bug, so that is worked around here.

This allows visibility into early boot of Ironic nodes and should
help get to the bottom of a frequent failure we're seeing in the gate.

Related-Bug: #1393099
(cherry picked from commit ffd66ad77ff07fff9812836b832bbcd952a61fff)

---

This also squashes the following commit into this patch. It is a required
fix to get grenade passing properly with the above changes:

commit 9eb8177eb7afa1e1cc9c64f80d175a1cb658ea50
Author: Adam Gandelman <adamg@ubuntu.com>
Date:   Fri Nov 21 09:41:45 2014 -0800
Move sgabios setup to hypervisor-ironic

This moves setup of sgabios ROM to the ironic hypervisor library.
This is failing to backport to juno because of an error in the sideways ironic
grenade. install_ironic() is expected to setup only python things and happens
earlier than initial package installation.

Fixes-bug: #1396352

Change-Id: Ifd18851e2d23d198d36e67883a81afc6a92d2a58

results summary at the end of subunit-trace. This is accomplished by

test run. By adding the elapsed time to the view it makes it easier
to track the performance of the run.

commit_message:
Switch to elapsed time in subunit-trace summary

This commit switches the time output to the elapsed time instead of
the total time in the results summary at the end of subunit-trace.
This is accomplished by just measuring the time delta right before
we begin processing the result stream until right after. While this
is not the most accurate method to measure the elapsed time, it
should be sufficient.

Previously just the total time was shown which could be misleading
since it is just the sum of the execute time for the individual test
methods (excluding the test fixtures). When running in parallel this
number would usually be a fair bit larger than the elapsed time of the
test run. By using the elapsed time instead it makes it easier to track
the performance of the run.

Change-Id: I7a1113c7f1333389b1b42249cafc4a45d630cb9f

commit_message:
Avoid oslo.messaging 1.5.0

1.5.0 dropped the fake_rabbit option which was still used by some
projects.  It was reintroduced in 1.5.1.

Change-Id: I47138da02c58073b03e3fb40537cc6f0b6a94a3c
Related-bug: #1399085
(cherry picked from commit c13842a06f2bcce7e65292ac75e0d6f44af08255)

@Anish,
Thanks for the update, first off, welcome and thanks for putting this together.  I'll ask that you return the favor and bear with myself and others as reviews can be frustrating.

Number of things not really addressed from my prior comments.  Most importantly it seems like maybe it would be good to study the existing code a bit more.  I've included a link to github that shows how the iser driver is in fact implemented, wondering if maybe you would like to experiment with that and build the spec off of that.  This would allow considerably more detail IMO and maybe clear up questions for folks that may not be overly familiar with iscsi HBA's.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 12088, 'date': '2014-10-28 18:43:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Hi John, I am aware of the iSER support. I based my work off of a previous spec for moving iSER support into the iSCSI driver (I mentioned this in the spec as well) seen here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86637/

That spec in particular delas with deprecating the separate iSER driver as it is essentially a slightly modified iSCSI driver and merging this functionality into the iSCSI driver, hence the approach I've chosen.

My plan was to make the interface support as generic as possible, hence I chose this approach (as opposed to as a separate driver or modifying iSER driver)"}, {'account_id': 12088, 'date': '2014-10-28 18:45:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Also, if you can specify what I missed from previous comments, I'll elaborate on that"}, {'account_id': 12088, 'date': '2014-10-29 22:16:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 12088, 'date': '2014-10-29 22:18:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Fleshed out problem description more, made wording of iSER more clear to indicate I'm not trying to duplicate pre-existing iSER driver, add link to another relevant spec/blueprint.

Tried to improve Abstraction point noted earlier, but this might be a terminology issue as I'm not sure what an abstraction is supposed to cover."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-29 22:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use devstack-logs macro in docker jobs

The docker jobs were explicitly running SCP to copy their job logs but
did so poorly by unsetting the keep hierarchy option. Switch these jobs
to the devstack-logs macro so that they are always up to date and
correct.

Change-Id: Ib311b23aa12e788918bda1f39d64728a384f5017

commit_message:
Remove ovs-vsctl call from OVSInterfaceDriver

ovs_lib module is responsible for the interaction with OVS but
OVSInterfaceDriver._ovs_add_port() method calls directly
ovs-vsctl which implies inconsistencies: ovs_lib calls ovs-vsctl
with a timeout but not OVSInterfaceDriver._ovs_add_port().

This change moves ovs-vsctl call in OVSInterfaceDriver._ovs_add_port
to ovs_lib.

Closes-Bug: #1396489
Change-Id: I4d03f8beef2c5f2366ad2d1cf5f0b18b4f2857cd

commit_message:
adjust default cpu and ram allocation ratios

As per support discussion, modify:

nova_cpu_allocation_ratio = 2.0
nova_ram_allocation_ratio = 1.0

Also add commented entry to user_variables to allow overriding

Conflicts:
	rpc_deployment/inventory/group_vars/nova_all.yml

Change-Id: I5563374a6e950f81e1e013d6e741993c1846ded6

Add NOVA_API_VERSIONS

This provides a mechanism for overriding v2 endpoint with v2.1 so that
tests can be run against a devstack to provide equivalency between the
APIs.

Also added several test cases for domains so if someone wants

commit_message:
Fix hostname validation for nameservers

Fixes the hostname validation to align with the RFC's demands[1].
This was done by replacing the full regex with a function that
broke the FQDN into individual components that were easier to
reason about with regular expressions.

Also added several test cases for domains so if someone wants
to convert it back to pure regex there will be better test vectors.

1. RFC 1123 says an all-digit hostname is allowed in section 2.1. It
   says that this more liberal syntax MUST be supported.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/test_attributes.py

Closes-Bug: #1396932
Change-Id: I003cf14d95070707e43e40d55da62e11a28dfa4e
(cherry picked from commit 35662d07628452d14306f5197871ad64f6396ff3)

commit_message:
adjust default cpu and ram allocation ratios

As per support discussion, modify:

nova_cpu_allocation_ratio = 2.0
nova_ram_allocation_ratio = 1.0

Also add commented entry to user_variables to allow overriding

Change-Id: Idad618068ef888dfb1c6c44c6dcd99b3c3aaaf64

commit_message:
Add retries for cinder get test

This fails as the volume service takes >10 seconds to start.
Adding retries is better than increasing the delay as it prevents
unnecesary waiting.

Closes #353

Change-Id: I9fc7023fa179c3b820c022730eead3685b0a94b4

commit_message:
Update i18n translation for Brocade plugin log msg's

All the log messages now have the required hints. In addition to
this debug messages are not translated.

This is done for the plugins/brocade directory.

Change-Id: I2ac926fd72037bb8f0605267ad50472c447ae83d

commit_message:
Remove check_uptodate.sh check from tox.ini

This removes the check_uptodate.sh test from the pep8 env. It
also syncs the sample config one last time to document some new
options available to users running with the newer oslo.messaging
versions.

Change-Id: I6107b996d5da808c3222696a9549ee06c22f80b9
Closes-bug: #1399085

commit_message:
Avoid oslo.messaging 1.5.0

1.5.0 dropped the fake_rabbit option which was still used by some
projects.  It was reintroduced in 1.5.1.

Change-Id: I47138da02c58073b03e3fb40537cc6f0b6a94a3c
Related-bug: #1399085

Mostly LGTM on the face of it, but IMO, you should not have to change tests for a refactoring like this. I would prefer the existing tests work and new tests were added for the new utility module.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2014-11-27 02:51:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Randall, thanks for the review/comments.

One thing I want to point out is that revising the test cases is always a side-effect.  In this case, I was proposing a removal of 'get_instance_names()' method from InstanceGroup for example.  This method is not used in any resource implementation other than in test cases.

One of the side-effects of revising the test cases is efficiency.  For example, the previous version says this when checking size of a group: "len(group.get_instances())".  The revised version will do "grouputils.get_size(group)".  The efficiency improvement here is that the revised version won't do any of the lambda sorting job before returning a list.

I do agree that some test cases for the newly added module are needed. commit_message:
Extract group functions into a utility module.

This patch extracts group checking functions into a dedicated module so
that resource implementations are simplified.  The module could later be
used by the autoscaling engine as well.

Change-Id: I99cdd8c9e8fe377e6923ab047a9c2ef08d1defad
partial-blueprint: reorg-asg-code
partial-blueprint: as-lib

commit_message:
Fix enable_metadata_network flag

The following patch: 9569b2fe broke the desired functionality of
the enable_metadata_network flag, by not allowing the metadata
proxy to be spawn for 'metadata networks', which are used for
accessing the metadata service when the logical router is not
implemented through the l3 agent.

This patch enables spawning of the metadata proxy for metadata
networks when the appropriate flag is set to True.

The patch also adds rather pedant unit test coverage for the
should_enable_metadata method which previously had no unit test.

Change-Id: I8dca1fce9fbc83e75ba7e4ce948531427bf7e88b
Closes-bug: 1394020

commit_message:
Add more TLS protocols to rabbit impl

Python 2.7.9 added PROTOCOL_TLSv1_1 and PROTOCOL_TLSv1_2, so these
are added to the allowed kombu_ssl_version values.

See https://docs.python.org/2/library/ssl.html#ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1_1

Change-Id: I1dd590d916ab524284a941db91b9cb81fd4639bb

Since we don't support multitenancy yet, we should just pop the
parent id of a project. When keystoneclient supports mulittenancy
we should bring everything in at once (CRUD), and these changes
should be removed.

Change-Id: I82c7c825502124a24ccdbadf09ecb2748887ca5d
"}]
commit_message:
Safely pop project parent id

Since we don't support multitenancy yet, we should just pop the
parent id of a project. When keystoneclient supports mulittenancy
we should bring everything in at once (CRUD), and these changes
should be removed.

Change-Id: I82c7c825502124a24ccdbadf09ecb2748887ca5d

commit_message:
Changed Project members list style, added scrolls

On current implementation, when a user request to modify project
members, a modal appears with a list of available members, the
buttons may go very far down from screen if the members list is
large.

Co-Authored-By: Joanna H. Huang <joanna.huitzu.huang@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I33912345329cee51b9ce7cd3d658b90d08b142a5
Closes-Bug: #1269910

commit_message:
Cell empty value defaults to - removing redundancy

The default value empty_value for a cell is horizon/tables/base.py
is "-", it is redundant and unnecessary to specify this column
definitions.

Closes-Bug: #1398904
Change-Id: Ica3e8f1559effe6b11f4e81d303758a869acbe2b

commit_message:
Warn user if needed when the process is forked

This change warns the library consumer when the process if forked and
we can't be sure that the library work as expected.

This also add some documentation about forking oslo.messaging Transport
object.

Change-Id: I2938421775aa72866adac198d70214856d45e165
Related-bug: #1330199

commit_message:
Remove unmaintained functional tests

This commit removes test_api which provides some functional tests
which we have not kept up. Instead functional tests should be added
to our tempest integration which runs automatically per commit.

Change-Id: I5ad7040c6dd9fa0c07f9e3c039629b040df11ee9

commit_message:
Set GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=5 in /etc/default/grub

* This gonna give some time to VM to make
  hard drives fully available. Othewise kernel
  could encounter VFS syncing issue. This case
  is quite hard to reproduce.

Change-Id: I2128f5b0a894231454b5bcc540b8991394f89ed4
Related-Bug: 1396078

we can pass it to the method if necessary.

commit_message:
Update i18n translation for Metaplugin plugin

All the existing LOG.info, LOG.warning, LOG.error and LOG.critical
messages should have _LI, _LW, _LE and _LC respectively. Also, debug
level log shouldn't be translated. This patch set will cover the
metaplugin directory.

Change-Id: I34437019fc8ffc38f11114d1d83dce54170ab989
Partial-Bug: #1320867

commit_message:
Rely on VM UUID to fetch metrics in libvirt

VM instance name is inconsistent between nova parent node and nova cell node.
So it is necessary to rely on VM UUID (which is an unique ID and immutable for VM
resource) rather than instance name to fetch system metrics via libvirt’s
lookupByUUIDString API.

Change-Id: I59dad915185fb191b7712024697e7b15e9e759e4
Closes-bug: #1396473

commit_message:
Show the creation time for stack snapshots

Creation time for snapshots is an important attribute,
we should return the creation time when doing stack
snapshot actions.

Change-Id: Ieaedaf79bf073737ec41fba2d0252d3f4ddc0fcf
Closes-Bug: #1398307

commit_message:
Add CPU pinning data to InstanceNUMACell  object

We will use this object to hold the data about CPU pinning for each
instance. We add the CPU pinning and topology information to each
InstanceNUMACell. We will use this information to track pinning of each
instance.

[{'created': '2014-12-04 19:29:25.000000000', 'message': "Remove solum.conf.sample from source control

We have a tool--literally tools/config/generate_sample.sh--
capable of creating a perfect sample config file at will.
Using it only to check that the sample in source control is right
doesn't make a lot of sense; I think if we trust its opinion so
strongly we ought to make it work for us.

If we decide we do want to keep a sample conf in source control,
I think we ought to manually generate it and keep it in doc/ with
a note about when it was last generated.

I've modified tox.ini to remove the check_uptodate job, as it's no
longer necessary. A lot of these config options are the result of
upstream dependencies whose updates are out of our control.

I've also modified our devstack lib script to generate the file
instead of copying it from the old place.

Change-Id: Ia204de5f4b571f68a3e5242eba2c0eafda7f0a5c
"}]
commit_message:
Remove solum.conf.sample from source control

We have a tool--literally tools/config/generate_sample.sh--
capable of creating a perfect sample config file at will.
Using it only to check that the sample in source control is right
doesn't make a lot of sense; I think if we trust its opinion so
strongly we ought to make it work for us.

If we decide we do want to keep a sample conf in source control,
I think we ought to manually generate it and keep it in doc/ with
a note about when it was last generated.

I've modified tox.ini to remove the check_uptodate job, as it's no
longer necessary. A lot of these config options are the result of
upstream dependencies whose updates are out of our control.

I've also modified our devstack lib script to generate the file
instead of copying it from the old place.

Change-Id: Ia204de5f4b571f68a3e5242eba2c0eafda7f0a5c

commit_message:
Add info on creating a tftp map file

This add instructions on how to create a tftp map file to the
install-guide. Also remove hard coded section numbers from iPxe
section.

commit_message:
Remove RpcCallback class

All users of the RpcCallback class have been converted to directly
define the oslo.messaging Target so this compatibility class is no
longer needed.

This is the final change of blueprint drop-rpc-compat.

Change-Id: I25474569850f3f2c176e7eee7aafa7ff0180b809

commit_message:
Convert several uses of RpcCallback

Convert several places in the code that were using the RpcCallback
compatibility class.  This class eased the transition to
oslo.messaging.  This patch drops the usage of this class in favor of
direct usage of the appropriate oslo.messaging API.

Part of blueprint drop-rpc-compat.

Change-Id: I955958e836635d43dabc7b39d050c1418b18cf8f

commit_message:
Fix up an old RpcProxy assumption

This patch fixes one last bit of code that assumed that the base
PluginApi used RpcProxy.  This code is now fixed to use the proper
oslo.messaging APIs instead.

Part of blueprint drop-rpc-compat.

Change-Id: I4adc321c07e6b5ad45a01f163b4c7e1ab74bcafd

subject: Remove RpcProxy class

commit_message:
Remove RpcProxy class

All users of this class have now been converted to use oslo.messaging
APIs directly, so this compatibility class can be removed.

Part of blueprint drop-rpc-compat.

Change-Id: Ife5c96d2d737694b9e79fe079d62dc48f23c033a

commit_message:
Update i18n translation for Embrane plugin

All the existing LOG.info, LOG.warning, LOG.error and LOG.critical
messages should have _LI, _LW, _LE and _LC respectively. Also, debug
level log shouldn't be translated. This patch set will cover the
embrane directory.

Change-Id: I89cf8e63311f96c3f1759a6c885d1b98e6fed598
Partial-Bug: #1320867

commit_message:
Revert message catalog compile

Change I26fac0ccf8fd4818e24618d56bf04b32306f88f6 brought in this
message catalog compile which is unrelated to the original issue.  I'm
assuming it is from a bad merge.  It creates issues because gettext
isn't installed on fresh systems (although in openstack infra it is
already there thanks to other dependencies).

See also Id0efa75edde38640512a5ff6e0b5ef8d2ac5bb62

Change-Id: Ia7677c2474fa5e9de8be4e5f4a3ef634ecb19177

Add logging to volume check_attach

Some failures in check_attach are only logged as tracebacks which lack
some useful information.  Log this useful information at the failure
point.

commit_message:
Cap oslo.messaging at <1.5.0

The new release of 1.5.0 introduced some backward incompatable
changes (fake_rabbit was removed) and config changes that make
current stable/juno config samples stale.

Closes-bug: #1399085
XXX: pulling from gate

Change-Id: I2a40bb983af82b6c5af90551d10d07f4ea820e58

commit_message:
Adds the my_ip value to the cinder.conf

This adds the my_ip value which is defaulting to the container address
which causes the iscsi mount problems. This is an issue in Juno +.

Change-Id: Ie1e3d4dbecad97e43a43bcd4ca404a3c30740bd0
Closes-Bug: 1398924
(cherry picked from commit a311a5e38b8a37b54577806d0a3ac05cc13fcf94)

commit_message:
Don't use module importutils from oslo-incubator

* Syncs latest module service
  Removes its dependency for oslo-incubator module importutils.
  Removes code which was never executed after switched to oslo.messaging.
Include changes:
5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
6ede600 rpc, notifier: remove deprecated modules

* config.genrator has been removed from oslo-incubator, so update
config.generator to use importutils from oslo.utils directly.

* Removes module importutils

Change-Id: If5cf4100006b5ca4dba1ad92e0c8efc22f90083c

commit_message:
Remove the config checks from tox file

This patch removes the sample config checks
from the tox.ini file.

We'll stop gating on this as it's just a big fat
pain when external libs change.

Instead, we'll start generating this in an external
job and publishing somewhere.

Change-Id: I1edb5f314f032fd4e038976d77de9751672b47ba

commit_message:
Fixes incorrect Cloudbase-Init glossary entry

Cloudbase-Init is a project written from the ground up to provide
Cloud-Init like features on Windows, but it's not a port of the actual
Cloud-Init project.

Change-Id: I6dffa21a4c3423939a1dd58eb57a0032ac591493
Closes-Bug: #1399323

commit_message:
enable microservice

move implementation specific configurations in server.py to
v2/reference module. Making the server.py only responsible
for loading dispatchers which are configured in monasca.conf
file. This change will enable any dispatcher to be loaded
according to the configuration file. For example, to config
two dispatchers to be served on a server, a monasca.conf
file can look like the following:

[DEFAULT]
dispatcher = v2_ref_metrics
dispatcher = v2_ref_alarms

If all the reference dispatchers should be served out of
one server, then the configuration file may look like this:

[DEFAULT]
dispatcher = v2_ref_metrics
dispatcher = v2_ref_alarms
dispatcher = v2_ref_alarm_definitions
dispatcher = v2_ref_events
dispatcher = v2_ref_transforms
dispatcher = v2_ref_notifications

One can use the configuration to load any dispatchers which
may be developed by third party. This way, to load new
dispatchers, one only needs to change the configuration file.

This patch set makes the API server a true miscroservice
server.

Change-Id: I87005f8ff4807e4c818057f1e7866001482a50e1

commit_message:
Fixes client to send 0 for min/max size

Previously, if 0 is passed as the min_size or max_size for a
configuration, the Trove client would ignore it and not put it in the
dict making up the request body. This changes that code to explicitly
check if this value is not None instead of ignoring it if its zero.

Co-Authored-By: Craig Vyvial <cp16net@gmail.com>

Fixes bug: 1398995

Change-Id: I7f1d196b00a612365576bfb82fbfd35d647588d4

commit_message:
Check for valid entries in gerrit/projects.yaml

Rename check_upstream_url_scheme.py to check_valid_gerrit_projects.py
and extend the check so that:
* It shows all errors, not only the first one
* It checks that the keywords are valid

This was triggered by seen twice in a week the keyword "description"
misspelled.

Script now outputs in error case:
Error: Upstream URLs should use a scheme in ['https://', 'http://', 'git://'],
 found git@://github.com/emonty/cookiecutter-openstack.git in
 openstack-dev/cookiecutter
Error: Unknown keyword 'decription' in project stackforge/ec2-driver
Found 2 error(s) in /tmp/projects.yaml

Also add the usual license header.

Change-Id: I334dcadc6fd4472fb28d379aec317c1a16dee2e2

subject: Fix Ironic modules so services properly run in Juno
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-04 19:41:15.000000000', 'message': "Fix Ironic modules so services properly run in Juno

Initially, the module was not creating an ironic.conf file and now
it does.  The configurations that are being put into the ironic.conf
file come straight out of the documentation.

The package 'python-pbr' is required and was not being installed
elsewhere so it is installed by the init module.

The ironic-conductor service requires the execution of 'ironic-dbsync'
before it can be active.

In the params module, the 'RedHat' packages and services were named
incorrectly or were otherwise missing.

Conflicts:
	manifests/keystone/auth.pp

Change-Id: I6922959fb0b732e24f9890fef8757e03ec5d3acb
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Ironic modules so services properly run in Juno

Initially, the module was not creating an ironic.conf file and now
it does.  The configurations that are being put into the ironic.conf
file come straight out of the documentation.

The package 'python-pbr' is required and was not being installed
elsewhere so it is installed by the init module.

The ironic-conductor service requires the execution of 'ironic-dbsync'
before it can be active.

In the params module, the 'RedHat' packages and services were named
incorrectly or were otherwise missing.

Conflicts:
	manifests/keystone/auth.pp

Change-Id: I6922959fb0b732e24f9890fef8757e03ec5d3acb

[{'created': '2014-12-04 18:30:39.000000000', 'message': 'Invert post build script status logic

We had the logic in the post build script conditions inverted. We
unfortunately need to say onsuccess: False and onfailure: False to make
this run on every job regardless of its build status.

This is because the plugin treats those options as IFFs with onsuccess
being evaluated first. So if onsuccess is set to True then the post
build script will run if and only if the build status was successful.
Similar story for onfailure. If we set them both to false then neither
success nor failure is checked and we should run the script on all
builds.

Change-Id: I70fd948e239e8a5007b0f5813c9d5757a1742abe
'}]
commit_message:
Invert post build script status logic

We had the logic in the post build script conditions inverted. We
unfortunately need to say onsuccess: False and onfailure: False to make
this run on every job regardless of its build status.

This is because the plugin treats those options as IFFs with onsuccess
being evaluated first. So if onsuccess is set to True then the post
build script will run if and only if the build status was successful.
Similar story for onfailure. If we set them both to false then neither
success nor failure is checked and we should run the script on all
builds.

Change-Id: I70fd948e239e8a5007b0f5813c9d5757a1742abe

commit_message:
VMware: Fix problem transferring files with ipv6 host

Need to protect the host name with '[' and ']' before
we create a http/https connection

Change-Id: I9320c47f446d1e6b6b088802c3916a88b118d9cf
Closes-bug: #1390906

commit_message:
Begin moving some of the common code to a shared base

To enable the addition of a new lockfile impl that
has some of the similar functionality as the existing impls
in pylockfile we need to break out what will be shared and
what will not be shared by the existing impls and the soon
to be added new impl.

Change-Id: I3fddfb05b78657ebed1449f0389004061e7e7082

commit_message:
Added helper decorator to log method arguments

The decorator originates from Neutron [1]. It's used there to log
arguments for oslo.messaging cast()/call() methods useful when debugging
interactions between different services.

The original version of the decorator was extended to work correctly for
class methods. Static methods are out of scope for this particular
decorator.

The original name of the decorator was also changed (log ->
log_method_call) to reflect the fact that it's designed for methods
only, not to be used as a general logger helper for any callable. If one
is needed, we need to introduce another generic decorator for all
callables that won't distinguish between first argument and the rest.

The plan is to merge the decorator into oslo.log and then adopt it in
oslo.messaging itself to make logging facility not specific to Neutron.

Added a simplistic unit test to check that decorator works as expected
for both object and class methods.

[1]: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/neutron/tree/neutron/common/log.py

Change-Id: I8436c954076fdc42482dec8e88f3075f055d425e

that are performed in `check_for_db`, and add missing check for
GLANCE_DB_USER.

commit_message:
Allow building docker image from anywhere

Record the image directory path to a variable and use it instead of the
current directory to allow the build script to work independently of the
location.

Closes-Bug: 1398648

commit_message:
Use job-template for publishing to ci.openstack.org

Merge the various publishing jobs into a job template. The only
difference between them was the target and that the system-config one
used zuul_swift_upload_console_log.

The template now uses zuul_swift_upload_console_log for all the jobs.

The jobs using the template are now named "{name}-ci-docs" and needed to
be added to the jjb project and renamed in the zuul layout file.

Change-Id: I8772508ec9da4ba4b7d3bc37f85d260f80e836bc

commit_message:
Defer loading Secret meta-data until requested

This change will cause all attributes on a Secret to be lazy-loaded,
meaning it will be possible to get the payload from a Secret object
without also pulling the meta-data (which was not previously an option).

Change-Id: Iea51f9aae580eb5cada81de697c3b14c179a01af

Fixes the hostname validation to align with the RFC's demands[1].
This was done by replacing the full regex with a function that
broke the FQDN into individual components that were easier to

Also added several test cases for domains so if someone wants
to convert it back to pure regex there will be better test vectors.

   says that this more liberal syntax MUST be supported.

Change-Id: I003cf14d95070707e43e40d55da62e11a28dfa4e

"}]
commit_message:
Fix hostname validation for nameservers

Fixes the hostname validation to align with the RFC's demands[1].
This was done by replacing the full regex with a function that
broke the FQDN into individual components that were easier to
reason about with regular expressions.

Also added several test cases for domains so if someone wants
to convert it back to pure regex there will be better test vectors.

1. RFC 1123 says an all-digit hostname is allowed in section 2.1. It
   says that this more liberal syntax MUST be supported.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/test_attributes.py

Closes-Bug: #1396932
Change-Id: I003cf14d95070707e43e40d55da62e11a28dfa4e
(cherry picked from commit 35662d07628452d14306f5197871ad64f6396ff3)

Fixes endpoint_filter tests

The tests were written incorrectly and only worked because SQLite
doesn't enforce foreign key relationships by default.

implements bp tests-on-rdbmses

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-01 19:45:53.000000000', 'message': "Raise ValueError for offset on Timestamp over limit

We can't order a Timestamp with an offset larger than 16 hex digits
correctly, so we raise a ValueError if you try to create one.

Change-Id: I8c8d4cf13785a1a8eb7416392263eae5242aa407
"}]
commit_message:
Raise ValueError for offset on Timestamp over limit

We can't order a Timestamp with an offset larger than 16 hex digits
correctly, so we raise a ValueError if you try to create one.

Change-Id: I8c8d4cf13785a1a8eb7416392263eae5242aa407

commit_message:
Fix container quota check during cross-account COPY

Container quota is not currently checking Destination-Account header
which could cause quota to not be enforced in case of copies

Change-Id: I43adb0d7d2fc14ba6c0ca419a52a5c3f138f799a
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiago@redhat.com>

The position information comes about when the option is registered, so it isn't a property of the option itself but a property of the relationship between the option and the ConfigOpts instance where the option is being registered. Although only command line options are positional, it is actually possible to register them multiple times on multiple ConfigOpts objects. So, rather than adding a numerical attribute to the Opt instance, where it might be reset if the options are rebuilt, we should just store a list of the command line options in the ConfigOpts instance. That way we don't even have to sort, we can just process the options in order in the list."}, {'account_id': 11391, 'date': '2014-11-25 04:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-11-25 05:20:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix wrong order of positional args in cli

Positional arguments were incorrectly parsed because instead of
original order there was an alphabetical.

This patch brings a positional field in Opt class and then sorts
all arguments by position-name.

Change-Id: Ia22654442b895c3f62834428f0ec6c3e8af22ebb
Closes-Bug: 1392428

commit_message:
Add Syntax job for os-ansible-deployment

This patch inserts a syntax check (using ansible-playbook
--syntax-check) before the existing lint job. The lint tool throws
exceptions on invalid playbooks so it makes sense to check for syntax
first.

Exclusions from syntax checking:
 * Playbooks that use vars_prompt due to ansible bug
   https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/9607

 * os-service-config-update.yml as it attempts to include a role based on
   a variable that isn't available at syntax check time.

Change-Id: I724bf0b8b3dd1e4bf3b1bd5a24b2c62eee912efb

[{'created': '2014-11-25 22:39:39.000000000', 'message': "Add job that tests rally and tempest integration

Rally has `rally verify` command that simplify usage of tempest.
It includes installation, tempest.conf generation, execution of tempest,
parsing and storing result to db.
As well there are such things like show results in different formats and
compare results of 2 runs.

Currently this functionality is partialy tested by gate-rally-dsvm-cli
But this job is more like tempest functional testing that doesn't fit
to this case well. E.g. we can run different rally commands but can't see
output in the way that we won't + we don't have enough flexiblity.

New job will trigger bash script, that will run set of rally commands
and publish results. So output will look similar to our perormance jobs:

http://logs.openstack.org/56/132556/9/check/gate-rally-dsvm-rally/36aa202/

commit_message:
Add job that tests rally and tempest integration

Rally has `rally verify` command that simplify usage of tempest.
It includes installation, tempest.conf generation, execution of tempest,
parsing and storing result to db.
As well there are such things like show results in different formats and
compare results of 2 runs.

Currently this functionality is partialy tested by gate-rally-dsvm-cli
But this job is more like tempest functional testing that doesn't fit
to this case well. E.g. we can run different rally commands but can't see
output in the way that we won't + we don't have enough flexiblity.

New job will trigger bash script, that will run set of rally commands
and publish results. So output will look similar to our perormance jobs:

http://logs.openstack.org/56/132556/9/check/gate-rally-dsvm-rally/36aa202/

Change-Id: Ibe105c596fa305e7d8bcd2ba90e8b9ed303f9b40

commit_message:
Add Castellan project

Castellan is a Key Manager interface for OpenStack projects that do not
want to integrate with Barbican directly.  Barbican will provide an
implementation of this interface, but projects can choose to implement
the interface with an alternative Key Management System if Barbican does
not meet their requirements.

A CR has laso been sent to the governance repo to add Castellan to the
Barbican program:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/138875/

Change-Id: I076e04e5167e2ff00b94142e86c242de36e766da

commit_message:
Make separate Bay objects for each bay object

The previous list code was not creating separate bay objects per
bay object returned by the server with the new versioned objects
code.  This results in getattr not able to retrieve the value of
the attribute resulting in no content.

Change-Id: I2bd7efe73871e6d9783683ba9301ca10f381a9fc

commit_message:
Recent patch missed called method def

The change https://review.openstack.org/136093 introduced a call to
_prepare_message_catalog_compilation but not the method defintion.

Adding the defintion of the method. Missing method is causing
django_openstack_auth jobs to fail in juno.

Change-Id: I081fcf7cd45ccbf2079316fd3068877dc384d0c4

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-11-28 14:15:31.000000000', 'message': 'Enable console and log for system z guests

If the host architecture is system z (s390, s390x), the interactive
console and the log of instances will be defined as "console" devices
(instead of "serial" devices) in libvirts domain XML. These console
devices need to have a "target type". For the interactive console this
is "sclp" and for the log "sclplm".

Partial-Implements blueprint libvirt-kvm-systemz

Change-Id: I20d5e32fee660e77c52b6fc5fdf1128a996bb994
'}, {'created': '2014-12-01 11:31:16.000000000', 'message': 'Enable console and log for system z guests

If the host architecture is system z (s390, s390x), the interactive
console and the log of instances will be defined as "console" devices
(instead of "serial" devices) in libvirts domain XML. These console
devices need to have a "target type". For the interactive console this

commit_message:
libvirt: Enable console and log for system z guests

If the host architecture is system z (s390, s390x), the interactive
console and the log of instances will be defined as "console" devices
(instead of "serial" devices) in libvirts domain XML. These console
devices need to have a "target type". For the interactive console this
is "sclp" and for the log "sclplm".

Partial-Implements blueprint libvirt-kvm-systemz

Change-Id: I20d5e32fee660e77c52b6fc5fdf1128a996bb994

subject: Libvirt: Don't let get_console_output crash on missing console file.

commit_message:
Libvirt: Don't let get_console_output crash on missing console file.

During a migration, the console file may be configured, even though
the file itself is not yet present. This patch prevents a
ProcessExecutionError which gets thrown by the chown if the file
doesn't exist.

Change-Id: Ifd75ae911fc264f8284ec3f2adbf1d73bc8c4aca
Related-Bug: #1292339

commit_message:
Add an identity backend method to get group by name.

We already support a get_user_by_name method, but an equivalent
one for groups is missing. This is needed for enhancements to
our federation mapping engine. This patch provides this new
method.

This patch does not expose this functionality as part of the
REST API, it is only supported at the manager/driver level.

Partially implements: bp mapping-enhancements

Change-Id: I2508a99125d9aec2a66b3b48e63c9b1ed2fe12a4

commit_message:
Remove flush_operations in the volume usage output

flush_operations is not used by upper layer code and also
according to
ftp://libvirt.org/libvirt/java/javadoc/org/libvirt/DomainBlockStats.html
http://libvirt.org/ruby/api/Libvirt/Domain/BlockStats.html

seems the last value should be errs instead of flush_operations
so remove it from libvirt driver layer.

Change-Id: I438b6fa40e9d97e3ffddda03919c5d577e91c155

commit_message:
Scheduler: return a namedtuple from _get_group_details

Commit 459ca56de2366aea53efc9ad3295fdf4ddcd452c added the utility
method _get_group_details. This patch returns a namedtuple that
contains the hosts and policies for the instance group. This makes
the code easier to read and more robust.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I76208092b06408022f48b1d965b982af86c78161

commit_message:
Remove aliases for `args` and `env` in utils

To remove aliases for `arg` and `env` functions in novaclient.utils,
we should use `arg` and `env` directly from cliutils in novaclients modules.

This patch removes aliases in `novaclient.utils` and starts using
`args` and `env` from novaclient.openstack.common.cliutils directly.

Change-Id: I4585adae62bc66ad6bc9d19be10d4679bb3dc5a1

subject: Use `arg` and `env` from cliutils: v1_1/shell

commit_message:
Use `arg` and `env` from cliutils: v1_1/shell

To remove aliases for `arg` and `env` functions in novaclient.utils,
we should use `arg` and `env` directly from cliutils in novaclients modules.
This is the first stage: change usage in novaclient.v1_1.shell

Change-Id: I237f0473844de49db8a4b141a9a71603c9ac76a7

commit_message:
Add manila tarball and release-tags jobs

It's a server project and so needs to explicitly list these jobs
(which most non-server projects get from the publish-to-pypi
template).

Change-Id: I9be5eb1f7ad0264ce91a677ecda99d5cc0c493a1

commit_message:
VLAN support for Distributed Virtual Router (DVR)

This blueprint proposes enhancement to existing
DVR infrastructure,  enabling it to embrace
VLAN networks as dvr interfaces.  It also proposes
enhancements that will enable DVR to route between
VLAN and VXLAN/GRE networks, thereby closing a
parity gap of DVR with centralized router.

DocImpact
Blueprint: neutron-ovs-dvr-vlan
Change-Id: I0273af2f6ea0084aa0943ebcee5875b3c9a472ba

commit_message:
Remove selinux from os-svc-install element-deps

os-collect-config depends on os-svc-install, so non-tripleo images
are getting tripleo selinux policies installed on them. This is
making o-r-c runs much slower for no benefit (and sometimes making
o-r-c exit with an error http://paste.openstack.org/show/135018/)

Change-Id: I90a8fb67e688ed068b5e7123e76aeced9af968b1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-11-26 20:22:36.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing broken while loop in imports.py

Issue: flake8 occasionally encounters "H302  import only modules."
error even though the python module exists at the path and python
shell is able to import the same.

Root-cause: The while loop in is_module_for_sure() had a bug, where
iterating variable, 'mod_name', was getting derived from the same
input, 'mod', every time. It should have led to an infinite loop
otherwise. But, an ImportError takes it out of the loop. Most of
the cases, this is not an issue, if as part of the exception handler,
built-in __import__() finds the module. The evidence of the issue is
the availability of import statements suffixed with "# noqa" to
work-around the bug.

Fixing the while loop causes the logic to flow in the original path of
the code to use 'imp.find_module()'.

Back-porting the change originally submitted for master.

Change-Id: I45a6dddcc497a563b37ae602542c0ce5a3e7db5e
'}]
commit_message:
Fixing broken while loop in imports.py

Issue: flake8 occasionally encounters "H302  import only modules."
error even though the python module exists at the path and python
shell is able to import the same.

Root-cause: The while loop in is_module_for_sure() had a bug, where
iterating variable, 'mod_name', was getting derived from the same
input, 'mod', every time. It should have led to an infinite loop
otherwise. But, an ImportError takes it out of the loop. Most of
the cases, this is not an issue, if as part of the exception handler,
built-in __import__() finds the module. The evidence of the issue is
the availability of import statements suffixed with "# noqa" to
work-around the bug.

Fixing the while loop causes the logic to flow in the original path of
the code to use 'imp.find_module()'.

Back-porting the change originally submitted for master.

Change-Id: I45a6dddcc497a563b37ae602542c0ce5a3e7db5e

commit_message:
Fix installing 3.13 kernel and other packages

* Added explicit installing 3.13 kernel in postinstall section
  because we use several different repositories and
  if we upgrade a node installer tries to
  find kernel only in one of them.
* Added 'yum update' and 'apt-get upgrade'
  to make sure all packages are up to date

Closes-Bug: 1399205
Change-Id: I12742735311f5d49f92d3dde845c15262e9f8372

commit_message:
VMware: pass vm_ref to _get_and_set_vnc_config

In the spawn refactor we get the vm_ref when the instance is created.
Passing it to the method _get_and_set_vnc_config saves a function
call. We are able to do this as we already have the vm_ref for the
instance in question.

Change-Id: I7b8d056af7f49ebd31beff2876edb9e6115d0a2c

commit_message:
change group acl's for os-ansible-deployment project

- allow os-ansible-deployment core group to approve reviews for master, stable/* and proposed/* branches
- allow os-ansible-deployment-release to create tags and new branches

Change-Id: If1ada9841d5de4a0f584c9e765056d273a579932

commit_message:
Fixed quotas double decreasing problem

When we delete vm with status "soft-delete" we shouldn't change
quota values because they were changed during soft-deleting.

Closes-bug: #1333145
Change-Id: I3ed7b3245b8908faa02903c74503918f061016bd

commit_message:
use openstackclient in keystone_user

This is based on the wip in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134843/
and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134844

This commit allows the keystone_user type to use the openstack provider.

When determining which opts are positional and which are optional,
we need to support both short (prefixed with a single -) and long

take care of both cases.

commit_message:
Check for short opts too

When determining which opts are positional and which are optional,
we need to support both short (prefixed with a single -) and long
(prefixed with --) options.  Just checking for a leading - should
take care of both cases.

Change-Id: I72a07125260a81232b479a3765717a5631b67f65

owner_name: Chris Hoge (not involved in upstream development)
commit_message:
Refactored help string generation

Refactored code to generate configuration help strings into its
own private function. The motivation is to use the same function
to generate help strings for both configuration parameters
(existing functionality) and parameter groups (to be added).

Partial-Bug: #1395819

Change-Id: I2c0fd50d50081c633fb50e89eb8c6a84d948f7cc

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-03 18:18:55.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing broken while loop in imports.py

This commit is backporting commit 64ef5bf5. It could not be
cherry-picked, as the unit test code had lot more dependent code to be
pulled in.

Issue: flake8 occasionally encounters "H302  import only modules."
error even though the python module exists at the path and python
shell is able to import the same.

Root-cause: The while loop in is_module_for_sure() had a bug, where
iterating variable, 'mod_name', was getting derived from the same
input, 'mod', every time. It should have led to an infinite loop
otherwise. But, an ImportError takes it out of the loop. Most of
the cases, this is not an issue, if as part of the exception handler,
built-in __import__() finds the module. The evidence of the issue is
the availability of import statements suffixed with "# noqa" to
work-around the bug.

Fixing the while loop causes the logic to flow in the original path of
the code to use 'imp.find_module()'

Change-Id: I421a66242121b987b7c8c1568394478514073b87
'}]
commit_message:
Fixing broken while loop in imports.py

This commit is backporting commit 64ef5bf5. It could not be
cherry-picked, as the unit test code had lot more dependent code to be
pulled in.

Issue: flake8 occasionally encounters "H302  import only modules."
error even though the python module exists at the path and python
shell is able to import the same.

Root-cause: The while loop in is_module_for_sure() had a bug, where
iterating variable, 'mod_name', was getting derived from the same
input, 'mod', every time. It should have led to an infinite loop
otherwise. But, an ImportError takes it out of the loop. Most of
the cases, this is not an issue, if as part of the exception handler,
built-in __import__() finds the module. The evidence of the issue is
the availability of import statements suffixed with "# noqa" to
work-around the bug.

Fixing the while loop causes the logic to flow in the original path of
the code to use 'imp.find_module()'

Change-Id: I421a66242121b987b7c8c1568394478514073b87

commit_message:
Fixed keystone cache vip for dogpile

The keystone cache vip was being pinned to the internal lb vip address
this causes issues with consistant hashing in caches and removes the
requirement for having memcached on a vip address powered by the
LB.

Change-Id: I6aaecbbf0ebf5aa2433d68e8c139ddfff810c973
Closes-Bug: 1398649

commit_message:
Fix rsync copying folders

Use --keep-dirlinks to allow rsync copy files to
destination path which is a symlink.

Required because of a commit to devstack:
https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/commit/81a016dbcd7bbf9fde791386fcc294fca0a59d71

Change-Id: I47b42adfc70175f5af675573975815066171eac1
